\title{Reflections on Two Moving Mirrors: \\
A Simpler Formulation of Special Relativity}

\author{Paul A.I. Reilly + collaborators tba\\
\textit{Independent Researcher}\\
\textit{Email: [relative.generalist@gmail.com}}

\date{11/12/2025}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Einstein's special relativity, while mathematically correct, contains a subtle conceptual flaw: it treats rest mass as invariant and requires external energy for acceleration. We show that by treating energy $E$ (rather than rest mass $m_0$) as the invariant quantity, and allowing mass to vary as $m = E/\gamma$, the theory becomes simpler and more physically intuitive. Clocks slow because they have less mass-energy to run on, not because of geometric path effects. This resolves classic paradoxes (twin, ladder) as simple geometric projections. The framework naturally incorporates energy conservation and eliminates the need for infinite acceleration energy. 

The mathematical structure underlying this reformulation is Euclidean $\mathbb{R}^4$ with signature $(+,+,+,+)$ rather than Minkowski spacetime with signature $(-,+,+,+)$. In this ``Reilly timespace,'' coordinate time $t$ is absolute and universal while proper time $\tau$ is path-dependent. The relation $dt^2 = d\tau^2 + dx^2 + dy^2 + dz^2$ leads naturally to $E^2 = m^2 + \vec{p}^2$ with mass and momentum perpendicular in four-dimensional Euclidean space. We call this framework ``That From Nat''---extending Wheeler's ``It from Bit'' by showing how information (measured in natural units) generates physical reality. This paper establishes the special-relativistic foundation; subsequent work will develop information-theoretic implications and connections to gravity, quantum mechanics, and cosmology.
\end{abstract}

\textbf{Keywords:} Special relativity, time dilation, light clock, Wheeler's ``It from Bit'', information physics, Reilly timespace

\section{Introduction}

In 1905, Einstein introduced his light clock thought experiment to demonstrate time dilation in special relativity \cite{Einstein1905}. The elegant simplicity of this gedankenexperiment---light bouncing between two mirrors while the apparatus moves---has made it a cornerstone of relativity pedagogy for over a century. Yet beneath its mathematical success lies a subtle conceptual assumption that, when examined, suggests an alternative interpretation of relativistic kinematics.

Einstein's derivation implicitly treats the clock's rest mass as invariant during acceleration. When the clock gains velocity $v$ relative to the laboratory, its ``moving tick rate'' slows by the Lorentz factor $\gamma = 1/\sqrt{1-v^2/c^2}$, a result verified countless times through particle decay rates, atomic clocks in aircraft, GPS satellite corrections, and muon lifetimes \cite{HafeleKeating1972,Allan1985,Will2001,FrischSmith1963}. The mathematical framework of special relativity built on this foundation---Minkowski spacetime with signature $(-,+,+,+)$ and Lorentz covariance---has proven extraordinarily successful.

However, a simple question reveals the hidden assumption: \textit{Where did the kinetic energy come from?} If the clock acquired velocity $v$ from an external source, then its total energy $E = \gamma m_0 c^2$ grows without bound as $v \to c$, requiring infinite energy input to reach lightspeed. If instead the clock used its own internal energy to accelerate---as energy conservation would seem to demand---then its mass must decrease as $m = m_0/\gamma$, and the clock runs slow simply because it has less energy available to operate.

This paper explores the second possibility. We show that by treating energy $E$ (rather than rest mass $m_0$) as the invariant quantity, and allowing mass to vary as $m = E/\gamma$, we obtain a reformulation of special relativity that is mathematically equivalent to Einstein's version but conceptually simpler and more physically intuitive. The framework naturally incorporates energy conservation, eliminates the ``infinite energy to lightspeed'' problem, and resolves classic pedagogical paradoxes (twin, ladder/barn) through straightforward geometric projection rather than counterintuitive symmetry arguments.

The mathematical structure underlying this reformulation is Euclidean $\mathbb{R}^4$ with signature $(+,+,+,+)$ rather than Minkowski spacetime with signature $(-,+,+,+)$. In this ``Reilly timespace,'' coordinate time $t$ is an absolute, universal parameter---all observers agree on its value---while proper time $\tau$ is path-dependent and measured by physical clocks. The fundamental relation is:
\begin{equation}
dt^2 = d\tau^2 + dx^2 + dy^2 + dz^2
\end{equation}
from which the energy-momentum relation $E^2 = m^2 + \vec{p}^2$ follows naturally, with mass and momentum perpendicular in four-dimensional Euclidean space. Clocks run slow when moving not because of some mysterious geometric path effect, but because $m = E/\gamma$ means the clock literally has less mass-energy to operate with.

We emphasize that this reformulation makes no new experimental predictions at currently accessible energies---it is a reinterpretation, not a revision, of special relativity's mathematical content. Both formulations give identical numerical results for all known tests. The advantages are pedagogical and foundational: students need not grapple with ``relativity of simultaneity'' paradoxes or wonder about infinite acceleration energies; the physics becomes more intuitive, the mathematics simpler, and the connection to deeper principles (energy conservation, information theory) more transparent.

This work emerges from three decades of reflection on Einstein's thought experiments and their implications. The title honors Robert Carlitz, who taught that the simplest questions often conceal the deepest insights. As Wheeler demonstrated with his ``It from Bit'' proposal \cite{Wheeler1990}, fundamental physics sometimes requires questioning assumptions so basic that they seem beyond examination. Here we question whether rest mass, rather than energy, should be taken as the invariant quantity in relativistic mechanics.

The paper proceeds as follows. Section 2 analyzes Einstein's light clock in detail, exposing the hidden assumption of constant rest mass and showing how relaxing it leads to variable mass $m = E/\gamma$. Section 3 develops the mathematical structure of Reilly timespace with Euclidean signature $(+,+,+,+)$. Section 4 demonstrates how classic relativistic paradoxes dissolve in this framework. Section 5 compares our formulation with Einstein's, proving mathematical equivalence while highlighting conceptual advantages. Section 6 connects this work to information physics and Wheeler's vision, introducing our ``That From Nat'' program. Section 7 discusses experimental considerations and pedagogical implications. Section 8 outlines future research directions and calls for collaboration. We conclude with reflections on why this alternative formulation has remained largely unexplored, and what it might contribute to the ongoing quest for unification.

One final note: this paper represents the first in a planned series exploring connections between information generation, spacetime geometry, and quantum mechanics. The full framework---dubbed ``That From Nat'' in homage to Wheeler's ``It from Bit''---extends his vision by providing explicit mechanisms for how information (measured in natural units, or ``nats'') generates physical reality. Subsequent papers will develop the information-theoretic foundations and their implications for gravity, cosmology, and the structure of physical law. Here we focus on the essential first step: a simpler, more physical interpretation of Einstein's original insights.

\section{The Flaw in Einstein's Light Clock}

\subsection{The Standard Analysis}

Einstein's light clock consists of two parallel mirrors separated by distance $L$, with a photon bouncing perpendicular to the mirrors. In the rest frame of the clock, the photon travels distance $2L$ per round trip at speed $c$, giving period $T_0 = 2L/c$.

Now consider this clock moving horizontally at velocity $v$ relative to the laboratory frame. During the time $\Delta t$ that the photon travels from bottom mirror to top mirror, the clock moves horizontally a distance $v\Delta t$. The photon must therefore travel a diagonal path. By the Pythagorean theorem, this diagonal distance is:
\begin{equation}
d = \sqrt{L^2 + \left(\frac{v\Delta t}{2}\right)^2}
\end{equation}

Since the photon travels at speed $c$ in all frames:
\begin{equation}
c\frac{\Delta t}{2} = \sqrt{L^2 + \left(\frac{v\Delta t}{2}\right)^2}
\end{equation}

Squaring both sides and solving for $\Delta t$:
\begin{equation}
c^2\frac{(\Delta t)^2}{4} = L^2 + \frac{v^2(\Delta t)^2}{4}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
(\Delta t)^2 = \frac{4L^2}{c^2 - v^2} = \frac{(2L/c)^2}{1 - v^2/c^2}
\end{equation}

Therefore:
\begin{equation}
\Delta t = \frac{2L/c}{\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2}} = \gamma T_0
\end{equation}
where $\gamma = 1/\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2}$ is the Lorentz factor.

\textbf{Conclusion:} Moving clocks run slow by factor $\gamma$. This result has been verified experimentally countless times through particle decay rates \cite{FrischSmith1963}, atomic clocks in aircraft \cite{HafeleKeating1972,Allan1985}, GPS satellite corrections \cite{Will2001}, and muon atmospheric penetration. The mathematical prediction is unquestionably correct.

\subsection{The Hidden Assumption: Where Does the Energy Come From?}

The derivation in Section 2.1 is mathematically impeccable and experimentally confirmed. Yet it contains a subtle conceptual assumption: it treats the mirrors (and any clocks attached to them) as having fixed ``rest mass'' $m_0$ independent of their state of motion.

To see why this matters, consider the energetics. The moving clock has kinetic energy (in the laboratory frame):
\begin{equation}
K = (\gamma - 1)m_0 c^2
\end{equation}

As $v \to c$, we have $\gamma \to \infty$ and therefore $K \to \infty$. \textbf{Where did this infinite energy come from?}

\textbf{Option 1: External Energy Source}

If the clock was accelerated by an external agent (rocket engine, electromagnetic field, particle accelerator), then energy was injected from outside. The total energy $E_{\text{total}} = \gamma m_0 c^2$ increases without bound. This is the standard interpretation: rest mass $m_0$ is invariant, but total energy grows with velocity.

This interpretation is mathematically consistent but leads to conceptual difficulties:
\begin{itemize}
\item Infinite energy required to reach lightspeed (where does it come from?)
\item ``Relativistic mass'' $\gamma m_0$ is frame-dependent (problematic for local physics)
\item Energy conservation requires careful tracking of external source
\item The clock itself becomes a bottomless energy sink
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Option 2: Internal Energy Source}

Alternatively, suppose the clock uses its own internal energy to accelerate---like a rocket expelling mass, or an electric train drawing on onboard batteries. In this case, the clock's mass must decrease as it accelerates, since total energy is conserved:
\begin{equation}
E_{\text{total}} = mc^2 = \text{constant}
\end{equation}

As the clock gains kinetic energy (in the lab frame), it must lose rest energy. This gives:
\begin{equation}
m = \frac{E_{\text{total}}}{\gamma c^2} = \frac{m_0}{\gamma}
\end{equation}
where $m_0$ is the initial mass at rest.

\textbf{This is the interpretation we explore in this paper.}

\subsection{The Reilly Train: A Gedankenexperiment}

To make Option 2 concrete, consider an idealized electric train (in honor of Einstein's preference for railway thought experiments):

\textbf{The Reilly Train specifications:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Runs on frictionless magnetic levitation track
\item Powered by perfect matter-antimatter batteries (or at low speeds, conventional batteries---the physics is identical since battery potential energy contributes to mass)
\item Perfect regenerative braking (no energy losses)
\item All acceleration energy comes from onboard mass
\end{itemize}

When this train accelerates from rest to velocity $v$:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Initial state:} Mass $m_0$, velocity 0, total energy $E = m_0c^2$
\item \textbf{Final state:} Mass $m = m_0/\gamma$, velocity $v$, total energy $E = mc^2\gamma = m_0c^2$
\end{itemize}

The energy is \textbf{conserved}: $E = m_0c^2$ throughout!

\textbf{Mass consumed during acceleration:}
\begin{equation}
\Delta m = m_0 - m = m_0\left(1 - \frac{1}{\gamma}\right)
\end{equation}

For example, to reach $v = 0.866c$ (our $\xi = 60째$ case where $\gamma = 2$):
\begin{itemize}
\item The train consumes half its mass: $\Delta m = m_0/2$
\item Remaining mass: $m = m_0/2$
\item Energy unchanged: $E = m_0c^2$
\end{itemize}

As $v \to c$: $m \to 0$ (train uses up all its mass), but it can \textbf{never quite reach lightspeed} with finite initial mass.

\subsection{Why the Clock Runs Slow: Physical Mechanism}

If the train (and any clocks aboard it) accelerates using its own mass, then $m = m_0/\gamma$. The clock literally has less mass---and therefore less internal energy---when moving.

The photon bouncing between the mirrors does not slow down; it always travels at speed $c$. What slows down are the \textbf{physical clocks on the mirrors themselves}. Since all the clock's internal processes depend on its available energy, they must run proportionally slower.

Consider the Compton frequency of the clock:
\begin{equation}
\omega = \frac{mc^2}{\hbar}
\end{equation}

With $m = m_0/\gamma$, this gives:
\begin{equation}
\omega_{\text{moving}} = \frac{m_0 c^2}{\gamma\hbar} = \frac{\omega_0}{\gamma}
\end{equation}

Every internal oscillation slows by factor $\gamma$, not because of some mysterious ``time dilation,'' but simply because \textbf{the clock has less mass-energy to operate with}.

This resolves the conceptual tension: \textbf{Clocks slow down; time does not.} There is an absolute, universal coordinate time $t$ that all observers agree on. What varies is proper time $\tau$ measured by physical clocks, because physical clocks depend on mass-energy to operate.

\subsection{Einstein's Magical Clocks}

Einstein's original formulation contains another subtle issue: the clocks attached to the mirrors. In standard presentations, these clocks are assumed to maintain constant rest mass $m_0$ even as the apparatus accelerates. But clocks are physical objects with internal mechanisms---springs, oscillators, atomic transitions. Where does \textbf{their} acceleration energy come from?

If we assume an external source provides unlimited energy to accelerate both the mirrors and the clocks, we face the infinite energy problem. If instead we recognize that the clocks must use their own mass to accelerate, we arrive at $m = m_0/\gamma$ and recover the Reilly picture.

The geometric argument of Section 2.1 is not wrong---it correctly predicts the factor $\gamma$. But it obscures the physical mechanism: \textbf{the clock runs slow because it has less mass, not because light is taking a longer path.} The path argument is a kinematic description; the energy argument is a dynamic explanation.

\subsection{The Two Triangles}

The relationship between Einstein's formulation and ours can be visualized geometrically (see Figures 1-3). Consider a train that has accelerated to velocity $v = (\sqrt{3}/2)c$, corresponding to angle $\xi = 60째$ from the proper time axis and Lorentz factor $\gamma = 2$.

\textbf{Reilly Triangle (inscribed in unit circle):}
\begin{itemize}
\item Hypotenuse: $E = m_0$ (energy conserved on circle)
\item Base: $p = m_0v$ (momentum)
\item Height: $m = m_0/\gamma = m_0/2$ (depleted mass)
\item Relations: $\sin \xi = v/c$, $\cos \xi = 1/\gamma = m/m_0$
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Einstein Triangle (extended by factor $\gamma = 2$):}
\begin{itemize}
\item Hypotenuse: $E = \gamma m_0 = 2m_0$ (energy grows)
\item Base: $p = \gamma m_0v = m_0\sqrt{3}$ (momentum)
\item Height: $m_0$ (constant rest mass)
\item Relations: $\sec \xi = \gamma = E/m_0$, $\tan \xi = p/m_0$
\end{itemize}

Both triangles have the same angle $\xi$, giving:
\begin{itemize}
\item Same velocity $v = \sin \xi$
\item Same Lorentz factor $\gamma = \sec \xi = 1/\cos \xi$
\item Same proper time reading $\tau = t \cos \xi = t/\gamma$
\end{itemize}

\textbf{The key difference:} Reilly's triangle stays on the energy circle (conservation), while Einstein's extends beyond it (energy increases). Both give identical predictions for measurable quantities like clock readings and momenta, but provide different physical interpretations of why clocks slow down.

